---
title: Duck Breast with Kohlrabi and Lentils
description: At the Fresh Farm we love to create recipes that will make any home cook feel like a Michelin starred chef. We feel this recipe fits this brief
brilliantly! Orange glazed duck with high end restaurant, but tonight you’ll find it gracing your humble kitchen!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/crispy-confit-duck-leg-with-kohl-ac2ce208.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/crispy-confit-duck-leg-with-kohl-32da8cf7.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/crispy-confit-duck-leg-with-kohl-57a1c18e7417fef95c8b4568
author: HelloFresh
course: main course
time required: 45 minutes
servings: 2
cuisine: French
nutrition:
  calories: 325 kcal
  fat: 10 g
  saturated fat: 2 g
  carbohydrates: 29 g
  sugar: 13 g
  protein: 33 g
---

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Peel the @kohlrabi{1}, remove the top and
bottom and chop into 1cm pieces. Cut the top and bottom off the
@carrot{1}, peel and then chop into 1cm pieces. Slice the
@celery stick{1} widthways into strips ½cm wide. Cut the @red onion{1} in half
through the root, peel and then slice into thin half moons. Peel and grate the
@garlic clove{1}, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1} and zest and juice the
@orange{½}.

Pop the @green lentils{100%g} into a #pot{} of cold water and put on high heat.
When the water comes to the boil, reduce the heat to medium and let your lentils
bubble away for ~{20%minutes} or until they are tender. When cooked, drain in a
#colander{} and allow to cool.

Place a wide #saucepan{} on high heat and add a splash of @oil{}. When the oil is
hot, add your kohlrabi, carrot, celery and onion to the pan. Season with a
pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and then pop the lid on the pan.
Reduce the heat to medium and cook for ~{7-10%minutes} with the lid on.

Next, prepare the @duck breasts{2} by scoring the skin gently in a criss cross
pattern.

> Tip: Scoring the skin will help with melting the duck fat that is underneath
> the skin.

When your veggies have been cooking for ~{7-10%minutes}, remove the lid, add your
garlic and @balsamic vinegar{2%tbsp} and cook until your balsamic vinegar has
evaporated. Add the @chicken stock pot{1} and the @water{100%ml}. Stir to
dissolve the stock pot and then leave your veggies to simmer in the stock for
~{10%minutes} or until soft enough to eat.

Season each duck breast with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of
@black pepper{}. Put them skin-side down into a #frying pan{} on medium heat. As
the heat of the pan melts the duck fat under the skin, drain the fat into a
#bowl{}. Cook for ~{5-7%minutes}, until the skin is golden-brown and crispy.

Turn your duck over, brown the flesh side and add your orange juice and zest.
Roll your duck around in the juice and then transfer to a #baking tray{}. Roast
for ~{5-7%minutes} if you like your duck pink. Roast for ~{10-12%minutes} if you
like it well done.

When your duck is ready, remove from the oven and leave to rest on your
#chopping board{} for a couple of mins. When your veggies are cooked, add your
drained lentils to the pan and heat until piping hot. Taste to make sure you
are happy with the seasoning and add more salt and pepper if necessary.

Finish your lentils by stirring in your parsley and then spoon into deep
#bowls{}. Slice each duck breast into five slices and place on top. Drizzle over
the juices from the baking tray. Enjoy!